{"summary":"All three amendments are technically sound. The first removes unreachable validation branches, and the second and third identify real lineage/snapshot correctness bugs that can break idempotent repair or hide still-running work.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-17-bcf4f863","decision":"accept","rationale":"`normalized.starts_with('.')` already rejects both `\".\"` and `\"..\"`, so the later equality checks are unreachable. Removing them preserves behavior and makes the validation rule clearer and less misleading."},{"amendment_id":"fr-17-d6be598b","decision":"accept","rationale":"`record_bead_completion` ignores its `started_at` argument, while the runless update path selects only by `(bead_id, project_id)` when `run_id` is absent. After a same-project runless retry has already been finalized, replaying that completion becomes ambiguous, so the documented repair/idempotency path can fail after a partial snapshot or journal write."},{"amendment_id":"fr-17-c776961e","decision":"accept","rationale":"Start logic only rejects a different active bead, so it permits a second active attempt for the same bead under a different project/run. Snapshot reconciliation then collapses lineage to the newest attempt per bead, which can mark the milestone ready and clear `in_progress_beads` while an older attempt is still running in `task-runs.ndjson`, so this is a real state-consistency bug."}]}